│ stop({"edit_points": [[1174, 1183,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the │
│ Issue:\nThe reproducer shows LoopUnroll deciding to peel the last iteration   │
│ (PeelLast) by 1. During peeling, the pass adjusts the loop exit condition by  │
│ subtracting 1 from the comparison's RHS. In the given IR, the loop's exit     │
│ condition value (%ec) is computed in the header and used both for branching   │
│ in the header and again in the latch to decide whether to exit. The current   │
│ implementation modifies the original compare instruction directly, which is   │
│ shared by both header and latch branches. This unintentionally changes the    │
│ header's control flow one iteration earlier than intended, potentially        │
│ violating assumptions made by peeling and confusing correctness checks        │
│ (Alive2 reports the source may not reach a return under its analysis          │
│ constraints).\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- LoopUnroll: Peel 1 iteration of   │
│ %loop.header, PeelLast path taken.\n- The pass transforms the compare icmp eq │
│ i16 %iv, 100 into icmp eq i16 %iv, 99 (nuw nsw flags added later), and        │
│ constructs a peeled copy where the peeled compare (%ec.peel) checks icmp eq   │
│ i16 %iv.next.lcssa, 100.\n- The log shows the first transformation point      │
│ BasicBlock::splitBasicBlockBefore via SplitEdge called from peelLoop,         │
│ consistent with PeelLast setup of InsertTop/InsertBot blocks.\n- Critically,  │
│ the compare adjustment is performed by directly mutating the ICmp instruction │
│ retrieved via Latch->getTerminator()->getOperand(0). In this IR, that operand │
│ is %ec defined in the header, shared by header and latch, so the mutation     │
│ affects both branches.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe code in LoopPeel.cpp,  │
│ when PeelLast is true, obtains the compare (ICmpInst) by reading the latch    │
│ branch's condition, and then mutates the RHS of that ICmp in-place. This      │
│ assumes the compare is only consumed by the latch branch. However, in         │
│ canonical loops like this, the condition value is created in the header and   │
│ used by both the header and latch branches. In-place mutation thus changes    │
│ the header's branch decision too, shifting which path is taken before peeling │
│ (e.g., skipping the 'then' block one iteration earlier), which is not         │
│ intended by PeelLast. This shared-use mutation is the earliest transformation │
│ that introduces the behavioral discrepancy.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n-  │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp\n- Lines: 1174-1183\n- Change:   │
│ Instead of mutating the shared ICmp (%ec) in-place, create a new compare      │
│ instruction with the adjusted RHS and install it as the latch branch's        │
│ condition, leaving the header's use of the original compare                   │
│ untouched.\n\nProposed code replacement:\n\nCurrent code:\n\n  auto *Cmp =\n  │
│ cast<ICmpInst>(L->getLoopLatch()->getTerminator()->getOperand(0));\n          │
│ IRBuilder B(Cmp);\n  Cmp->setOperand(\n      1,                               │
│ B.CreateSub(Cmp->getOperand(1),\n                                             │
│ ConstantInt::get(Cmp->getOperand(1)->getType(), 1)));\n\nReplace with:\n\n    │
│ // Adjust the exit condition so the loop exits one iteration early.\n  // Do  │
│ not mutate a compare that may be shared with the header; instead\n  // build  │
│ a new compare and use it only for the latch branch.\n  auto *LatchBr =        │
│ cast<BranchInst>(L->getLoopLatch()->getTerminator());\n  Value *LatchCond =   │
│ LatchBr->getCondition();\n  auto *Cmp = dyn_cast<ICmpInst>(LatchCond);\n  if  │
│ (Cmp) {\n    IRBuilder B(LatchBr);\n    Value *AdjRHS =                       │
│ B.CreateSub(Cmp->getOperand(1),\n                                             │
│ ConstantInt::get(Cmp->getOperand(1)->getType(), 1));\n    Value *NewCond =    │
│ B.CreateICmp(Cmp->getPredicate(), Cmp->getOperand(0), AdjRHS);\n              │
│ LatchBr->setCondition(NewCond);\n  } else {\n    // If the latch condition is │
│ not an ICmp, conservatively bail.\n    return false;\n  }\n\nRationale:\n-    │
│ Ensures only the latch branch condition is modified for PeelLast.\n-          │
│ Preserves the header branch's original condition, maintaining correct         │
│ pre-peel control flow behavior.\n- Avoids unintended side-effects when the    │
│ compare is shared by multiple users.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy replacing the      │
│ in-place mutation of the shared compare with creation of a new, adjusted      │
│ compare used solely by the latch branch, we avoid changing the header's       │
│ control flow and respect the semantics of last-iteration peeling. This fix    │
│ addresses the earliest transformation causing the discrepancy and should      │
│ resolve the observed non-termination/return-reachability complaint in the     │
│ equivalence check, while keeping the intended exit-one-iteration-early        │
│ semantics intact."})                                                          │
